UV–Vis spectra of EA (5–25 ppm) in the pH range of 9–14 were scanned at room temperature (Fig. S2). Based on the concentration and absorbance data of the alkali-soluble EA aqueous solution at all pHs, a quantitative correlation between absorbance and concentration was determined using linear regression analysis (Fig. 4
                              ). The regression analysis results demonstrated a strong linear relationship between concentration (c) and absorbance for all samples, with a goodness of fit exceeding 0.997. This confirms full adherence to the Lambert-Beer law. The UV–Vis spectra of alkali-soluble EA at different pH values were compared at a concentration of 15 ppm (Fig. 5
                              a). At pH levels of 9, 10, and 11, the short-wave absorption peak generated by the π-π* jump split into 2 peaks at 252 and 274 nm, respectively. Additionally, the long-wave absorption peak at 356 nm is the result of an n-π* transition. As the pH increased, the short-wave absorption peaks of EA did not split but shifted red to 290 nm, while the long-wave absorption peaks shifted red to 248 nm. These significant changes in the UV absorption patterns of alkali-soluble EA likely resulted from the hydrolysis and deprotonation of the phenolic hydroxyl groups within the lactone structure of EA [61,66].

Table 5

 revealed EA solubility in nitrogenous solvents. The solubility of EA in nitrogenous solvents significantly improved, in contrast with the alcoholic solvents. The EA exhibited fluorescence emission properties in NMP, DMAC, DMF, and TEA. From the 3D fluorescence spectra (Fig. 8

) and fluorescence emission spectra (Fig. 9a) of EA in nitrogenous solvents, it is evident that the optimal excitation wavelength for EA in NMP, DMAC, and DMF is 370 nm. The emission spectrum features dual peaks: one near 407 nm with high fluorescence intensity, and a weaker one around 550 nm. The occurrence of the dual-emission phenomenon represented a violation of Kasha's rules [77]. For EA, each molecule contains two carbonyl groups (electron acceptors) and four phenolic hydroxyl groups (electron donors). Among these characteristics, the carbonyl group on the aromatic ring of EA exhibited a higher charge density in the excited singlet state, demonstrating enhanced conjugation with the aromatic ring compared to its behaviour in the ground state. However, the three nitrogen-containing organic solvents—NMP, DMAC, and DMF—all possess N and CO groups, which are highly prone to accepting hydroxyl protons from EA, facilitating the formation of hydrogen bonds. This leads to the conjugation of lone electron pairs with the aromatic ring, thereby altering the distribution of electron density and enhancing the electronic effects. This configuration is unfavourable for the conjugation of the carbonyl group of EA with the aromatic ring. These two distinct CT states corresponded to different stable conformations. The energy difference between these conformations results in the generation of double-emission fluorescence in EA [78]. Typically, the energy difference between the S1 and S2 excited states of such molecules is substantial, which consequently slows down the rate of the internal transition from S2 to S1 [79–81]. Consequently, the strong emission peak at 407 nm is attributed to the emission from the S2 excited state, while the weaker emission peak at 550 nm is attributed to the emission from the S1 excited state. The optimal excitation and emission wavelengths for the EA in the TEA solution were 400 nm and 471 nm, respectively, which were red-shifted, compared to the three solutions mentioned above. This is due to the higher viscosity of the TEA solvent, which is 280 mPa s at 35 °C, which constrains the movement of EA molecules, resulting in a red-shift for the emission wavelength. Another noteworthy phenomenon was observed in the three-dimensional fluorescence spectrograms of EA/TEA solutions (Fig. 8d). This phenomenon can be described as an inverse Kasha's rule red-edge effect, whereby the emission spectra of the fluorescence vary with the wavelength of the excitation light [77]. In 1991, Alexander P. Demchenko proposed a mechanism for the red-edge effect [82]. Due to the Boltzmann distribution, the molecules will have a part of the molecules in the higher vibrational energy level, in the rigid or highly viscous medium, the relaxation is blocked, so that the vibrational relaxation and solvent relaxation, the rotation rate of the molecules were very slow. Therefore, using longer-wavelength excitation light more readily excites higher energy molecules. These molecules, once excited, are more likely to relax to the vibrational energy levels of the ground state's excited state, resulting in naturally longer emission wavelengths [83,84] (see Table 6).

Table 11
 illustrates the relative fluorescence quantum yields (QY) of EA in 1,4-BDO, NMP, and DMSO, which increase as the solvent polarity increases. Previous research has demonstrated that the formation of hydrogen bonds leads to a decrease in the fluorescence quantum yield, and the strength of the excited state hydrogen bonds diminished with increasing solvent polarity [85,86], causing the QY of the EA molecule to decrease. Consequently, the QY of the EA molecule increases with increasing solvent polarity. The HOMO-LUMO energy level diagrams of EA in different solvents (Fig. 12
) were obtained from DFT calculations. From Fig. 12, it is evident that the molecular energy gap of EA in different solvents gradually decreased with increasing solvent polarity, and the fluorescence emission spectrum will be red-shifted. The emission peak of EA in 1,4-BDO is 407 nm, and it shows a strong emission peak near 407 nm and a weak emission peak around 550 nm in NMP, while the emission peak in DMSO is 515 nm, which is in line with the calculated results.
